    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that sounds good in theory but it feels like a stretch for a single cafe. if i have to raise my prices to pay everyone more, won't my customers just spend less because things are more expensive? it feels like a wash, or maybe even worse for me specifically. is there any actual evidence that this \"positive feedback loop\" works for a small shop owner, or is it more of an idealistic view?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The increased demand generated by higher wages is not an idealistic view; it is an observable reality in competitive markets. While some customers might reduce spending on non-essentials, the increased purchasing power of the entire community means more people are able to afford your cafe's goods. In a rural town, where local spending is concentrated, the boost in overall local demand from higher wages is a tangible benefit that outweighs the small price adjustments you must make.",
      "source": "target",
